WEBVTT

00:03.580 --> 00:05.210
♪ I've been tryin' to keep it
low, low, low ♪

00:05.210 --> 00:07.790
♪ Been tryin'
to make it on my own ♪

00:07.790 --> 00:09.290
♪ But you got something... ♪
Meredith:
Every day, we're surrounded

00:09.290 --> 00:13.080
by people who ask
how we're doing.

00:13.080 --> 00:15.120
So, do you
want to...

00:15.120 --> 00:17.290
say the Serenity Prayer
before you go in?

00:17.290 --> 00:18.710
♪ All the things
that you do to me ♪

00:18.710 --> 00:21.080
Okay. Uh,
just don't do drugs.

00:21.080 --> 00:22.830
[ Singsong voice ]
And have a nice day at school!

00:22.830 --> 00:25.080
♪♪

00:25.080 --> 00:27.790
But when surgeons
ask how you're doing,

00:27.790 --> 00:29.540
we genuinely care
about your answer.

00:29.540 --> 00:31.290
You okay?

00:31.290 --> 00:33.670
Just thinking about all the ways
I would have ditched school

00:33.670 --> 00:36.620
to go get high
when I was her age.

00:36.620 --> 00:39.080
So, what? You wanna
just stay here all day

00:39.080 --> 00:41.040
in case
she leaves or...?

00:41.040 --> 00:43.250
How many heroin overdoses
did you treat

00:43.250 --> 00:44.750
in the E.R. this week?
Hm.

00:44.750 --> 00:46.790
Let's just drive around the
school and make sure she
doesn't ditch out the back.

00:46.790 --> 00:48.250
-Okay.
-Okay.

00:48.250 --> 00:49.710
Your answer to
"How are you doing?"

00:49.710 --> 00:51.500
tells us how good
a job we're doing

00:51.500 --> 00:52.920
at taking care of you.

00:52.920 --> 00:55.290
Mnh. That was
an accident.

00:55.290 --> 00:57.170
You're the restaurant's
best server,

00:57.170 --> 00:58.750
and you accidentally
spill coffee

00:58.750 --> 01:00.790
on the most annoying
customer of all time?

01:00.790 --> 01:02.210
She totally
deserved it.

01:02.210 --> 01:04.420
-[ Gasps ] I knew it!
-[ Laughs ]

01:04.420 --> 01:06.960
You know, I had to pay
for her stupid, ugly
jacket with my tips.

01:06.960 --> 01:08.670
As I recall,
I chipped in.

01:08.670 --> 01:11.080
Unfortunately, caretaking
outside of medicine

01:11.080 --> 01:12.790
is usually more complicated.

01:12.790 --> 01:14.580
Your triple espresso.

01:14.580 --> 01:17.460
And I mailed in
your ballot.

01:17.460 --> 01:19.250
-Thanks.
-Yeah.

01:20.620 --> 01:21.580
Morning, Chief.

01:23.000 --> 01:24.580
Richie.

01:24.580 --> 01:25.750
Lincoln.

01:25.750 --> 01:28.170
[ Telephone rings ]

01:28.170 --> 01:30.080
-Did he just call you Richie?
-Yeah.

01:30.080 --> 01:32.120
He says if I insist
on extending his name,

01:32.120 --> 01:34.040
he's gonna shorten mine.
[ Chuckles ]

01:34.040 --> 01:35.830
Rude.
Oh, no, no, no.

01:35.830 --> 01:37.620
He's a good guy.
Mean guitar player.

01:37.620 --> 01:39.120
Yeah.
Link's the best.

01:39.120 --> 01:40.580
You know, we go all the way
back to undergrad.

01:40.580 --> 01:41.880
Oh?

01:41.880 --> 01:43.710
Oh, no! No, no, no.
Not like that.

01:43.710 --> 01:46.250
We just waited tables together.
He's like my brother.

01:46.250 --> 01:47.790
Okay, I'm gonna
head to the lab,

01:47.790 --> 01:49.170
but I hope
to see you later.

01:51.830 --> 01:53.830
I-I wasn't
too thrilled

01:53.830 --> 01:57.080
when I found out Catherine
and Koracick were...

01:57.080 --> 01:58.670
old friends.
Can I help you?

01:58.670 --> 02:00.580
♪♪

02:00.580 --> 02:02.670
[ Children shouting playfully ]

02:02.670 --> 02:07.460
♪♪

02:07.460 --> 02:09.710
[ Cellphone dings ]

02:09.710 --> 02:13.290
♪♪

02:13.290 --> 02:15.540
[ Cellphone clicking ]

02:15.540 --> 02:19.120
♪♪

02:19.120 --> 02:21.040
[ Cellphone dings ]

02:21.040 --> 02:23.040
♪♪

02:28.040 --> 02:30.040
♪♪

02:42.080 --> 02:44.210
How did you find me?

02:44.210 --> 02:45.420
You used to make Cristina

02:45.420 --> 02:48.380
get you coffee here
every morning.

02:48.380 --> 02:50.420
And I figured you wouldn't
be stupid enough to fly,

02:50.420 --> 02:51.750
all things considered.

02:51.750 --> 02:54.290
Pierce told you.

02:54.290 --> 02:56.670
Well, there goes
her license.

02:56.670 --> 02:58.120
We all know you're
not gonna sue Pierce.

02:58.120 --> 02:59.880
You have
bigger problems.

02:59.880 --> 03:02.210
♪♪

03:02.210 --> 03:04.250
[ Woman on P.A.
speaking indistinctly ]

03:04.250 --> 03:07.120
-Good morning.
-Morning, Parker.

03:07.120 --> 03:08.710
What do we got first?

03:08.710 --> 03:10.500
Cece Colvin.
Post-heart transplant

03:10.500 --> 03:12.210
with secondary
renal failure

03:12.210 --> 03:14.080
due to her
anti-rejection meds.
Mm.

03:14.080 --> 03:16.380
Uh, did you know she's
a professional matchmaker?

03:16.380 --> 03:17.540
Oh, I know.
[ Chuckles ]

03:17.540 --> 03:19.250
I had to show her pictures
of my girlfriend

03:19.250 --> 03:21.330
so she'd stop
trying to set me up.

03:21.330 --> 03:22.790
Hey.

03:22.790 --> 03:24.170
Welcome back,
Dr. Avery.

03:24.170 --> 03:25.750
Thanks, Parker.
Give us a minute, please.

03:25.750 --> 03:27.620
[ Elevator bell dings ]

03:28.960 --> 03:31.460
Wasn't sure if you were
reading any of my texts.

03:32.670 --> 03:34.750
Yeah. Um...

03:34.750 --> 03:36.750
You met a boy with, uh,
scapular osteochondroma,

03:36.750 --> 03:38.380
so you pressed pause
on your trip

03:38.380 --> 03:40.000
to fly him and his family
here to operate.

03:40.000 --> 03:41.580
Did you get my reply?

03:41.580 --> 03:43.210
You mean the letter "K"?
Yeah.

03:43.210 --> 03:44.920
I thought you were
a fan of brevity.

03:44.920 --> 03:47.080
Maggie.
Hold on, okay?

03:47.080 --> 03:49.080
I know my trip
was sudden.

03:49.080 --> 03:52.170
I know this is sudden.
I...

03:52.170 --> 03:53.830
I just really miss you.

03:53.830 --> 03:55.710
Okay? I want us
to be able to catch up.

03:55.710 --> 03:57.080
Take you
to dinner tonight.

03:57.080 --> 03:58.290
Uh...look.

03:58.290 --> 04:00.290
You've got surgery.
I've got patients.

04:00.290 --> 04:01.960
We can, uh,
catch up later.

04:01.960 --> 04:05.880
♪♪

04:05.880 --> 04:09.080
[ Woman on P.A.
speaking indistinctly ]

04:09.080 --> 04:12.750
Hey. Uh. I'm...sorry.
Am I late?

04:12.750 --> 04:16.670
Uh, no. Couldn't sleep,
so I got a head start.

04:16.670 --> 04:18.750
There is no way
we will get through

04:18.750 --> 04:20.330
all of these approaches
in one year.

04:20.330 --> 04:22.080
Well, we need
to narrow them down.

04:22.080 --> 04:24.420
We'll start with
molecular vectors only.

04:24.420 --> 04:26.540
Process of elimination.

04:26.540 --> 04:28.540
Alex: I need you to do
a surgical consult.

04:28.540 --> 04:30.500
-We're busy.
-Look, Grey, Shepherd, and Hunt

04:30.500 --> 04:32.120
took last-minute
personal days.

04:32.120 --> 04:33.750
So I need you to put
the future on hold

04:33.750 --> 04:35.580
and take care of the patients
that exist in the present.

04:35.580 --> 04:38.460
And your consult's in my office,
refusing to leave.

04:38.460 --> 04:40.210
Your husband's
a grouch.

04:40.210 --> 04:42.250
-You made him chief.
-You married him.

04:43.790 --> 04:45.580
DeLuca: Hey, hey.

04:45.580 --> 04:48.170
Howlin' Wolf Richie
sings the blues.

04:48.170 --> 04:50.380
Not at work? Right. Okay.
Sorry, Dr. Webber.

04:50.380 --> 04:52.000
Helm, Schmitt,
get over here.

04:52.000 --> 04:54.210
[ Siren wailing in distance ]

04:54.210 --> 04:57.710
Okay, Hunt is out,
so it's just us in the E.R.

04:57.710 --> 04:59.880
I'll handle the trauma.
The three of you take
the rest of the pit.

04:59.880 --> 05:01.790
Report to DeLuca here.

05:01.790 --> 05:03.750
Grey Sloan prides itself

05:03.750 --> 05:06.330
on providing the highest
level of patient care.

05:06.330 --> 05:08.290
Your colleague Dr. Roy

05:08.290 --> 05:10.290
was woefully short
in that department.

05:10.290 --> 05:12.500
I expect you
to do better.

05:12.500 --> 05:14.540
-Okay, let's move.
-Okay.

05:14.540 --> 05:15.920
Thank you, Dr. Webber.

05:15.920 --> 05:17.330
It's not a favor.

05:17.330 --> 05:19.250
What do we have here?

05:21.540 --> 05:24.380
You still owe me
a drink. Tonight?

05:24.380 --> 05:28.500
Oh, um, I don't know.
I-I might have a...thing...

05:28.500 --> 05:30.120
Woman: Dr. Kim,
we could use you on Bed 3.

05:30.120 --> 05:31.210
...later.

05:31.210 --> 05:33.580
Okay. Well,
if your thing changes,

05:33.580 --> 05:35.460
I'll be at Joe's.

05:35.460 --> 05:38.170
♪♪

05:38.170 --> 05:40.210
You turned down
a date? With him?

05:40.210 --> 05:42.170
What? [Chuckling]
No. It's not a date.

05:42.170 --> 05:45.120
He asked you out to drinks.
It's a date.

05:45.120 --> 05:49.040
♪♪

05:49.040 --> 05:51.330
[ Elevator bell dings ]

05:51.330 --> 05:53.170
Oh, hey, Karev.
Have I got a present for you.

05:53.170 --> 05:55.500
Thought you were
still on vacation.
Not a vacation.

05:55.500 --> 05:57.500
It was a personal leave while
I figured some stuff out.

05:57.500 --> 05:59.120
You're not at work,
it's a vacation.

05:59.120 --> 06:00.330
Searching for
the meaning of life

06:00.330 --> 06:02.710
just means
it's a boring vacation.

06:02.710 --> 06:04.040
What's the present?

06:04.040 --> 06:06.620
I've got an 11-year-old with
an extensive osteochondroma

06:06.620 --> 06:08.330
in both scapulae,
all right?

06:08.330 --> 06:09.750
Wildest case of it
I have ever seen.

06:09.750 --> 06:10.920
And it's pro bono.
Pro bono?!

06:10.920 --> 06:12.670
I've met the family.
How is that a present?

06:12.670 --> 06:15.080
We're bleeding money
out of every --

06:17.380 --> 06:19.500
Rafi, look who's here.
[ Chuckles ]

06:19.500 --> 06:21.040
Dr. Avery!

06:21.040 --> 06:22.750
[ Softly ]
You're welcome.

06:22.750 --> 06:24.670
Hey, buddy!

06:24.670 --> 06:26.120
♪♪

06:32.830 --> 06:34.620
[ Telephone ringing ]

06:34.620 --> 06:37.620
Ms. Sullivan?
Hi. I'm Dr. Bailey.

06:37.620 --> 06:38.670
This is Dr. Wilson --

06:38.670 --> 06:40.710
Karev.
Karev.

06:40.710 --> 06:42.040
I'm here for Dr. Grey.

06:42.040 --> 06:43.540
Yes, Dr. Grey
is unavailable,

06:43.540 --> 06:45.250
so we are
going to be the o--

06:45.250 --> 06:47.080
Wasting your time,
all right?

06:47.080 --> 06:49.500
I've already seen an internist,
two gastroenterologists,

06:49.500 --> 06:52.080
and two surgeons who ran
dozens of inconclusive test

06:52.080 --> 06:54.380
before diagnosing me
with acid reflux,

06:54.380 --> 06:56.580
anorexia, and anxiety,
none of which

06:56.580 --> 06:58.460
are actually the cause
of my stomach pain.

06:58.460 --> 07:00.120
So I'm here to see
the woman I read about --

07:00.120 --> 07:02.000
the best,
Dr. Meredith Grey.

07:02.000 --> 07:04.710
And you have both made it clear
that you are not her,

07:04.710 --> 07:07.580
so no thank you
and goodbye.

07:07.580 --> 07:09.500
Okay.

07:09.500 --> 07:11.420
Ms. Sullivan.

07:11.420 --> 07:14.000
I'm am not Meredith Grey.
This is true.

07:14.000 --> 07:17.460
But I am the woman
who taught Meredith Grey.

07:17.460 --> 07:20.790
Grey was a lump of clay
when I met her.

07:20.790 --> 07:23.380
And I shaped her
with my two hands

07:23.380 --> 07:25.330
into the surgeon
that she has become.

07:25.330 --> 07:28.080
And I helped her
with the mini livers.

07:28.080 --> 07:32.250
♪♪

07:32.250 --> 07:34.250
Dr. Karev is our chief
of pediatric surgery --

07:34.250 --> 07:36.250
well, right now
chief of everything.

07:36.250 --> 07:37.920
This is Rafi and Aamir.

07:37.920 --> 07:39.330
Thank you so much
for doing this.

07:39.330 --> 07:41.500
-You mind if I take a look?
-Of course.

07:41.500 --> 07:43.830
Hey, Rafi, can you lift your
arms above your head for me?

07:43.830 --> 07:45.170
-[ Grunts softly ]
-Oh, yeah.

07:47.080 --> 07:48.500
Alright.
How'd you guys meet?

07:48.500 --> 07:50.170
Uh, hiking in Oregon.

07:50.170 --> 07:52.080
We were both
at the same creek,

07:52.080 --> 07:54.420
and they made me
some amazing s'mores.

07:54.420 --> 07:57.250
Rafi loves to swim, even
when it's freezing outside.

07:57.250 --> 07:59.620
And skip rocks
and climb trees.

07:59.620 --> 08:01.710
-Basically anything outdoors.
-When Rafi was 8 years old,

08:01.710 --> 08:04.210
he was diagnosed with
multiple osteochondromas.

08:04.210 --> 08:06.460
They're benign overgrowths
in my bones and cartilage.

08:06.460 --> 08:07.880
They're hereditary.

08:07.880 --> 08:09.960
He explains it to people
about five times a day.

08:09.960 --> 08:11.380
Tell you what
we're gonna do here,

08:11.380 --> 08:13.210
is we're gonna shave
your bones down

08:13.210 --> 08:15.830
and reshape them
so they go from this...

08:15.830 --> 08:17.540
to...this.

08:17.540 --> 08:19.210
Aamir: You're sure we should
remove them now?

08:19.210 --> 08:21.210
His pediatrician said we might
want to wait till he's older.

08:21.210 --> 08:24.170
No. I want them off now!
They're weird.

08:24.170 --> 08:26.460
Jackson: That's okay. The
risk isn't any different
if we do it now or later.

08:26.460 --> 08:28.880
And he's in good hands. Avery
and I make an excellent team.

08:28.880 --> 08:30.670
Link: Sorry I'm late.

08:30.670 --> 08:32.960
I had to, uh,
put a pin in a tibia.

08:32.960 --> 08:35.040
What's up,
little dude?

08:35.040 --> 08:38.000
I'm Dr. Lincoln.
But you can call me Link.

08:38.000 --> 08:40.500
-He's on this, too?
-He's head of ortho. Yeah.

08:40.500 --> 08:42.500
Avery didn't tell me
you were in on this.

08:42.500 --> 08:44.170
Sweet.

08:44.170 --> 08:45.540
[ Flatly ]
Yeah. Sweet.

08:45.540 --> 08:48.540
♪♪

08:48.540 --> 08:51.170
Alright.
Your vitals look good,

08:51.170 --> 08:54.620
but I'd like to do another blood
panel and run another echo.

08:54.620 --> 08:56.580
And?

08:56.580 --> 08:59.460
A little birdie told me
Dr. Avery's back in town.

08:59.460 --> 09:00.830
[ Elevator bell dings ]

09:00.830 --> 09:03.830
It was that or talk
about myself, so...

09:03.830 --> 09:07.040
Ah. Yes, Cece. Dr. Avery
is back temporarily.

09:07.040 --> 09:08.380
He's here to do
a complex surgery,

09:08.380 --> 09:09.920
and then
he's off again.

09:09.920 --> 09:12.500
So you're sad he's in town
for such a short time.

09:12.500 --> 09:14.830
Sure.
Let's go with that.

09:14.830 --> 09:18.830
I'll be back to do your echo
after I finish my rounds.

09:18.830 --> 09:21.170
What happened
between them?

09:21.170 --> 09:22.620
-I don't know.
-Parker!

09:22.620 --> 09:24.670
[ Monitor beeping ]

09:24.670 --> 09:26.750
When I was 14,

09:26.750 --> 09:29.420
I got alcohol poisoning in
the middle of the school day.

09:29.420 --> 09:30.920
-Did I ever tell you that story?
-[ Chuckles ]

09:30.920 --> 09:32.830
Um, Bailey told me
there was this app

09:32.830 --> 09:34.750
you can put in your kid's phone
to track them.

09:34.750 --> 09:36.080
-Yeah. Already done.
-Oh.

09:36.080 --> 09:37.460
I'm not proud of it.

09:37.460 --> 09:40.380
And this app...
tracks her texts.

09:40.380 --> 09:41.920
Oh. That's a little...

09:41.920 --> 09:43.830
Invasive? Extreme?

09:43.830 --> 09:45.380
-Mm.
-There was this text

09:45.380 --> 09:47.420
about a bunch of kids
cutting class today.

09:47.420 --> 09:49.670
That's why we're here.
Listen, you're
a recovering addict

09:49.670 --> 09:53.460
raising a recovering addict,
and you care about her.

09:53.460 --> 09:54.670
That's gonna make
anyone a little...

09:54.670 --> 09:56.290
Insane?

09:56.290 --> 09:58.250
I was gonna say
obsessive.

09:59.790 --> 10:02.170
[ Inhales sharply ]
Delete them.

10:02.170 --> 10:04.250
If I do it, I will just
get sucked back in.

10:04.250 --> 10:05.750
[ Clicking ]

10:05.750 --> 10:07.380
Okay.

10:07.380 --> 10:09.330
[ Exhales sharply ]
[ Beeping ]

10:09.330 --> 10:10.670
All gone!

10:10.670 --> 10:13.000
No need to know the details
of her lunch...

10:13.000 --> 10:14.880
[ Cellphone clatters ]
...with Rachel and Eileen.

10:14.880 --> 10:16.500
[ Sweetly ]
They're having lunch?
Mm.

10:16.500 --> 10:18.040
That's good!
Mm-hmm.

10:18.040 --> 10:19.670
They seem
like nice girls.

10:19.670 --> 10:21.830
And it's so hard to make friends
when you transfer.

10:21.830 --> 10:23.880
[ Normal voice ] How did I
become this person?

10:23.880 --> 10:25.620
I kind of like
this person.

10:27.920 --> 10:30.000
DeLuca: Okay, Helm, go get some
ABD and conform to dress this.

10:30.000 --> 10:31.750
-Mm-hmm.
-Dr. Webber.

10:31.750 --> 10:33.620
Got a small lac on the forehead
and on the calf,

10:33.620 --> 10:35.960
but I just finished
repairing the leg.

10:35.960 --> 10:37.880
Hmm. Is there
a problem, Schmitt?

10:37.880 --> 10:39.790
The edges don't
want to line up.

10:39.790 --> 10:41.250
Well, I can see that.

10:41.250 --> 10:43.000
DeLuca, you have
any advice for him?

10:43.000 --> 10:44.830
Throw a corner stitch
on the apex first.

10:44.830 --> 10:46.040
Then the rest
will line up.

10:46.040 --> 10:48.080
Come on. You know that.
Right. Sorry.

10:49.920 --> 10:52.170
[ Sighs ]

10:52.170 --> 10:54.330
Look, um, Schmitt's just
a little distracted.

10:54.330 --> 10:56.080
I-I think he's got
a thing for Helm.

10:56.080 --> 10:58.710
Is that his excuse
or yours?

10:58.710 --> 11:01.250
It's not an excuse, Dr. Webber.
It's just an explanation.

11:01.250 --> 11:02.830
Well, you could
have fooled me.

11:02.830 --> 11:04.330
You and Schmitt were
on the same patient,

11:04.330 --> 11:05.830
and you didn't notice
that he needed help?

11:05.830 --> 11:07.210
Show some initiative,
DeLuca.

11:09.580 --> 11:12.330
I, uh -- I-I already
ate breakfast,

11:12.330 --> 11:14.000
if that's
what's happening.

11:14.000 --> 11:16.710
Oh, no. I have to make cookies
for Zola's bake sale.

11:16.710 --> 11:18.580
And they
have to be homemade

11:18.580 --> 11:20.290
because, apparently,
that's how you show you care.

11:20.290 --> 11:23.120
And Zola wants chocolate.
Not chocolate chip. Chocolate.

11:23.120 --> 11:24.460
And did you know
there's a difference

11:24.460 --> 11:26.960
between cocoa powder
and hot-chocolate mix?

11:26.960 --> 11:28.460
Not a baker?
I just learned

11:28.460 --> 11:29.670
that you had to
pre-heat the oven.

11:29.670 --> 11:31.120
Well, you know what?
You look busy.

11:31.120 --> 11:32.830
So I'm just
gonna take off.

11:32.830 --> 11:34.710
Oh, just stay.

11:34.710 --> 11:36.460
Make sure I don't
burn the house down.

11:36.460 --> 11:38.620
-Okay.
-See?

11:38.620 --> 11:40.330
You'll get to do
all of this soon --

11:40.330 --> 11:41.960
bake cookies,
look for childcare,

11:41.960 --> 11:43.500
find a good school.

11:43.500 --> 11:45.460
And there it is.

11:45.460 --> 11:47.210
Look, Meredith, I'm gonna
go back to Germany.

11:47.210 --> 11:49.620
I've got a great O.B.
in Landstuhl,

11:49.620 --> 11:52.040
and I'll give birth there
and raise the baby myself.

11:52.040 --> 11:53.330
And not tell Owen?

11:53.330 --> 11:55.710
Well, I was planning
to tell him,

11:55.710 --> 11:57.500
and I was
going to apologize

11:57.500 --> 11:59.380
for all the awful things
that I said to him,

11:59.380 --> 12:00.830
and then I came back here
and found out

12:00.830 --> 12:02.420
that they were all true.

12:02.420 --> 12:04.040
Oh. It's not
what you think.

12:04.040 --> 12:05.420
Oh...

12:05.420 --> 12:07.460
He's not living with
his ex-wife and two kids?

12:07.460 --> 12:09.250
Okay, well,
that part is true.

12:09.250 --> 12:10.830
But he's fostering a baby,

12:10.830 --> 12:13.330
and she's helping the mom
get her life together.

12:13.330 --> 12:15.830
I just...

12:15.830 --> 12:18.210
I-I don't see
how it would work.

12:18.210 --> 12:20.000
Then why are you here?

12:20.000 --> 12:21.380
-You stalked me.
-No, no.

12:21.380 --> 12:23.080
Why are you
in Seattle?

12:23.080 --> 12:25.580
And don't blame the clot
because we both know

12:25.580 --> 12:27.420
that you could jump
on a bus or a train

12:27.420 --> 12:29.460
if you really wanted
to get out of town.

12:29.460 --> 12:31.750
[ Fork scraping rapidly ]
I don't know, okay?
I don't -- Well, I-I just --

12:31.750 --> 12:34.290
I don't know why I'm here
or -- or what I'm gonna do.

12:34.290 --> 12:37.000
I've been holed up in
a very fancy hotel room

12:37.000 --> 12:39.460
running an exorbitant
room-service bill

12:39.460 --> 12:41.210
trying to figure it out,
and I still don't know.

12:41.210 --> 12:42.830
and it's driving me crazy
and pissing me off.

12:42.830 --> 12:45.170
And what are you doing
to those eggs?!

12:45.170 --> 12:46.920
[ Scraping stops ]
Here. Gimme.

12:48.460 --> 12:50.080
I don't need the fork.

12:57.960 --> 12:59.960
All right.
Let's see what we got here.

12:59.960 --> 13:01.790
[ Monitor beeping ]

13:01.790 --> 13:04.380
[ Machine whooshing ]

13:04.380 --> 13:06.000
Okay, here's
your mitral valve.

13:06.000 --> 13:08.460
So, why's Dr. Avery
in the doghouse?

13:10.290 --> 13:11.920
Let's focus
on you, okay?

13:11.920 --> 13:14.290
This is me
focusing on me.

13:14.290 --> 13:16.080
If something's
eating away at you,

13:16.080 --> 13:18.330
I'd just as soon
we get it out now

13:18.330 --> 13:21.170
before you have my heart
in your hands.

13:22.460 --> 13:25.210
It's the way he left.
He made this huge decision to go

13:25.210 --> 13:27.620
and then told me
by voicemail,

13:27.620 --> 13:29.670
then barely communicated
once he was gone.

13:29.670 --> 13:31.330
Who does that?

13:31.330 --> 13:33.580
I mean, I get having
big questions.

13:33.580 --> 13:35.880
So go. Go seek your truth,
follow your heart.

13:35.880 --> 13:37.830
Just don't freeze me out.

13:37.830 --> 13:39.790
What are
your big questions?

13:39.790 --> 13:41.500
[ Scoffs ]

13:41.500 --> 13:43.500
When is he coming back?

13:43.500 --> 13:46.500
Does he even want to be
in a relationship?

13:46.500 --> 13:48.120
Why does he keep texting me
pictures of trees?

13:51.120 --> 13:53.540
Not questions
about him.

13:53.540 --> 13:55.420
About you.

13:55.420 --> 13:57.080
♪♪

13:57.080 --> 13:58.670
[ Metal clanking ]

13:58.670 --> 14:04.500
♪♪

14:04.500 --> 14:06.210
Jackson: Link, how we
looking on your side?

14:06.210 --> 14:09.420
It's coming along.
Bone saw.

14:09.420 --> 14:11.120
Brooke was telling me
about your wedding.

14:11.120 --> 14:12.290
That sounds like
quite a day.

14:12.290 --> 14:13.960
-Brooke?
-Alex: He means Jo.

14:13.960 --> 14:16.120
Jo. Sorry. Still
getting used to that.

14:16.120 --> 14:17.540
[ Bone saw buzzes ]

14:17.540 --> 14:19.330
You guys knew
each other, then?

14:19.330 --> 14:20.960
School.
And we worked together.

14:20.960 --> 14:22.750
Oh. What hospital?
Jimmy's Crab Shack.

14:22.750 --> 14:24.620
Hey, Avery, how was
your leave of absence?

14:24.620 --> 14:27.750
♪♪

14:27.750 --> 14:29.790
[ Bone saw buzzes ]

14:29.790 --> 14:31.830
Uh, yeah, it's going great.
I got a few weeks left.

14:31.830 --> 14:33.500
I'm gonna head down
to Santa Barbara.

14:33.500 --> 14:36.250
Then I haven't decided
between Yosemite and Zion.

14:36.250 --> 14:38.210
-Ooh, Zion. Hands down.
-Really?

14:38.210 --> 14:39.960
Angels Landing --
it's up like 6,000 feet,

14:39.960 --> 14:41.500
and you're on this
teeny little trail

14:41.500 --> 14:43.000
with a chain
as a handrail.

14:43.000 --> 14:44.670
Yeah. I want
to try that.

14:44.670 --> 14:46.380
What about you, Chief?
You hike?

14:46.380 --> 14:49.120
-I'm from Iowa.
-The path report's back.

14:51.080 --> 14:53.750
Thought you said
it wasn't malignant.
Jackson: Damn it.

14:53.750 --> 14:56.880
Bailey: The HIDA scan
and the ERCP were negative.

14:56.880 --> 14:58.290
Jo: Which rules out

14:58.290 --> 15:00.540
the gallbladder
and biliary tree.

15:00.540 --> 15:02.960
Yeah. I told you that
a half-hour ago.

15:02.960 --> 15:05.120
Okay. We know that,
but this is how we work.

15:05.120 --> 15:07.380
Yeah, yeah. Process of
elimination. I get it.

15:07.380 --> 15:09.460
We do the same thing
down at my auto shop.

15:09.460 --> 15:11.920
I'm a mechanic, and I learned
everything I know from my dad.

15:11.920 --> 15:13.790
He ran that shop
for 45 years

15:13.790 --> 15:16.330
then retired
and passed it on to me...

15:16.330 --> 15:18.210
along with that lunch pail.

15:18.210 --> 15:20.460
Which you brought
for good luck?

15:20.460 --> 15:22.380
Which I brought with me
for lunch.

15:22.380 --> 15:24.460
I'm constantly fasting for all
the tests you doctors order,

15:24.460 --> 15:26.620
so I bring myself a sandwich
for when I'm done.

15:26.620 --> 15:29.290
Um, I want to run
a technetium scan

15:29.290 --> 15:32.290
to rule out
Meckel's diverticulum.

15:32.290 --> 15:34.580
It's not that.
You've been tested?

15:34.580 --> 15:36.790
No, but I read
about it online.

15:36.790 --> 15:39.790
Okay. The Internet does not
provide accurate diagnoses.

15:39.790 --> 15:42.790
Yeah, well, far as I can tell,
neither do you.

15:45.380 --> 15:47.710
Meredith: You were
the one who insisted

15:47.710 --> 15:49.790
that I tell Megan Hunt
about me and Riggs.

15:49.790 --> 15:51.380
Because you
were her surgeon.

15:51.380 --> 15:53.500
Because she deserved
all the information.

15:53.500 --> 15:55.500
Is that what
this is about?

15:55.500 --> 15:58.080
You blaming me for
breaking up you and Riggs?

15:58.080 --> 16:00.040
No. I broke up
me and Riggs.

16:00.040 --> 16:03.000
But Owen is my friend,
and Amelia is my sister.

16:03.000 --> 16:04.670
Right. [ Sighs ]

16:04.670 --> 16:06.750
Not about me.
You're his best friend.

16:06.750 --> 16:08.250
Well, I was.
Not anymore.

16:08.250 --> 16:10.290
I can't be.
Why?

16:10.290 --> 16:12.580
[ Scoop slams ]
Because I hate him,
Meredith.

16:12.580 --> 16:15.420
I hate him so much,
I want to smash his face in.

16:15.420 --> 16:17.500
I mean, I can't
even look at him.

16:17.500 --> 16:19.380
How the hell can I raise
a child with him?

16:19.380 --> 16:20.920
[ Cookie dough thuds ]

16:20.920 --> 16:23.250
I grew up without my dad

16:23.250 --> 16:27.540
because my mother hated him
too much to let him love me.

16:27.540 --> 16:29.790
One day, your kid will go
looking for their dad.

16:29.790 --> 16:31.710
They're not gonna find
a deadbeat or a drunk.

16:31.710 --> 16:34.580
They're gonna find a good man
who's devastated.

16:34.580 --> 16:37.040
Do you hate him enough
to do that to either of them?

16:37.040 --> 16:40.420
♪♪

16:40.420 --> 16:43.290
Amelia: Stop eating all his
snacks. I'm ordering food now.

16:43.290 --> 16:45.210
-Mm.
-Morning, folks!

16:45.210 --> 16:47.620
Jim Blomquist,
Vice Principal.

16:47.620 --> 16:49.620
The security guard said
you've been parked out
here a couple hours?

16:49.620 --> 16:52.040
Yeah, uh, we're waiting
for someone, a student.

16:52.040 --> 16:53.620
-Mm.
-Oh. You're parents?

16:53.620 --> 16:57.080
Uh, no. Yeah. Um...
Kind of hard to define.

16:57.080 --> 16:58.330
Uh...
[ Chuckles nervously ]

16:58.330 --> 17:00.420
Yeah. Betty Nelson,
uh, lives with us,

17:00.420 --> 17:03.250
and I foster her --
her baby, so...

17:03.250 --> 17:05.460
See? There's not really
a name for that.

17:05.460 --> 17:07.710
Well, you can't loiter
here in a school zone,

17:07.710 --> 17:09.790
so you're gonna
have to move on,

17:09.790 --> 17:11.250
Mr. and Mrs., uh...

17:11.250 --> 17:12.960
Uh, oh, no, no, we're --
we're -- Well, we're -- we're --

17:12.960 --> 17:14.880
We'll just go.

17:14.880 --> 17:17.580
Yeah. We're gonna go.

17:17.580 --> 17:19.830
Aamir: He has cancer?

17:19.830 --> 17:22.330
We caught it early.
That is good news.

17:22.330 --> 17:24.460
But we had it biopsied
more than once.

17:24.460 --> 17:26.460
Yes, I understand,
and things can change.

17:26.460 --> 17:27.830
They mutate,

17:27.830 --> 17:30.080
and if the specimen is not
taken from a cancerous area,

17:30.080 --> 17:32.170
then it goes undetected.

17:34.500 --> 17:37.750
Now, I can remove
the scapula entirely

17:37.750 --> 17:39.330
and take the cancer
with it.

17:39.330 --> 17:41.750
Or I can just
remove the growths,

17:41.750 --> 17:46.420
which would mean he'd require
radiation treatments,

17:46.420 --> 17:48.620
which can be dangerous
in a child this young.

17:48.620 --> 17:51.880
His mom died in childbirth.
He's all I have.

17:53.330 --> 17:55.380
If I remove the scapula,

17:55.380 --> 17:58.380
he is going to have severely
limited range of motion.

17:58.380 --> 18:01.170
His prosthetic's gonna have
to be replaced as he grows.

18:01.170 --> 18:04.580
But the cancer
will be gone.

18:04.580 --> 18:06.540
Okay? He'll live.

18:08.460 --> 18:10.420
I didn't want
to give you my s'more.

18:10.420 --> 18:12.920
What's that?
[ Exhales sharply ]

18:12.920 --> 18:15.670
When we saw you at the creek,
Rafi said,

18:15.670 --> 18:17.710
"That guy's all alone.
We should share."

18:17.710 --> 18:20.580
And I thought,
"I'm tired and hungry,

18:20.580 --> 18:23.880
and I don't want to give
a random stranger my dessert."

18:23.880 --> 18:26.380
But I did.
To make him happy.

18:26.380 --> 18:29.210
And now what --
what you're saying

18:29.210 --> 18:31.120
is that s'more
is gonna save his life?

18:31.120 --> 18:33.080
♪♪

18:33.080 --> 18:35.000
Thank you.

18:35.000 --> 18:37.540
Do what you need
to save him.

18:37.540 --> 18:39.080
I absolutely will.

18:47.460 --> 18:49.420
Ugh. There should be
an hour every day

18:49.420 --> 18:51.290
where this whole city
has to chill.

18:51.290 --> 18:53.000
Seattle Nap Time --
no one gets hurt,

18:53.000 --> 18:54.830
and we all get to go
to the bathroom.

18:54.830 --> 18:56.420
[ Elevator bell dings ]

18:56.420 --> 19:00.420
♪♪

19:00.420 --> 19:02.080
It's not a date.

19:02.080 --> 19:04.670
-Mm.
-I owe him a drink.

19:04.670 --> 19:06.250
Are you saying this...
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

19:06.250 --> 19:08.120
...so it's more surprising
when he kisses you?

19:08.120 --> 19:10.040
Hey, guys!
Wake up!

19:10.040 --> 19:11.290
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

19:11.290 --> 19:12.960
What the hell
happened?

19:12.960 --> 19:15.460
Uh, M-Molly Graham.
19 years old. Asthmatic.

19:15.460 --> 19:18.120
I gave her two nebulizers
and a shot of Solu-Medrol.

19:18.120 --> 19:20.250
-I'm monitoring her sats.
-No, you're not!

19:20.250 --> 19:22.330
She's tachypneic.
Her sats are in the 80s.

19:22.330 --> 19:24.710
She's decompensating, okay?
She's not moving any air around.

19:24.710 --> 19:26.830
Okay, we're gonna have to
intubate. Prep for RSI.

19:26.830 --> 19:28.620
-Don't we need an attending?
-Do you see one?

19:28.620 --> 19:30.120
I'll -- I'll get Webber.

19:30.120 --> 19:32.250
[ Molly gasping ]

19:32.250 --> 19:34.080
Okay. Hang in there
for me, Molly, okay?

19:34.080 --> 19:35.920
[ Air hissing ]

19:35.920 --> 19:38.500
Let's go, Helm.
Let's go.

19:38.500 --> 19:41.380
♪♪

19:41.380 --> 19:43.620
Okay.

19:43.620 --> 19:46.040
Come on. Come on.

19:46.040 --> 19:47.790
It's not going in.
Uh, okay, get a scope.

19:47.790 --> 19:49.710
[ Rapid beeping continues ]

19:49.710 --> 19:51.290
♪♪

19:51.290 --> 19:53.250
Come on, Molly.
It's okay. You got this.

19:53.250 --> 19:56.040
♪♪

19:56.040 --> 19:58.040
Let's go!
Give me that, Helm.

19:59.540 --> 20:02.330
Okay.

20:02.330 --> 20:04.120
Okay.

20:04.120 --> 20:06.920
Come on. Come on.
Got it.

20:06.920 --> 20:08.540
[ Beeping slows ]

20:08.540 --> 20:12.040
♪♪

20:12.040 --> 20:13.960
No. Helm, I got it.

20:13.960 --> 20:19.460
♪♪

20:19.460 --> 20:21.040
She was about to code.

20:21.040 --> 20:22.380
I didn't think you'd
want me waiting for you.

20:22.380 --> 20:24.000
You were right.

20:24.000 --> 20:26.880
But next time,
try including your intern.

20:26.880 --> 20:29.460
This is a teaching
hospital.

20:32.830 --> 20:35.250
Owen: So, is it like
a Magic 8-Ball?

20:35.250 --> 20:36.460
Amelia: Sort of.

20:36.460 --> 20:39.960
Except it's a lot easier
to hide in study hall.

20:39.960 --> 20:42.120
How have you
never seen one?

20:42.120 --> 20:44.000
Study hall
was for homework.

20:44.000 --> 20:45.830
We would not
have been friends.

20:45.830 --> 20:47.620
[ Chuckles ]
Okay. So...

20:47.620 --> 20:49.710
should we stay parked
out here all day?

20:49.710 --> 20:51.830
What do you think, Leo?
-Leo, what do you think?

20:51.830 --> 20:53.580
[ Paper rustling ]

20:53.580 --> 20:55.210
No? Nothing?

20:58.290 --> 21:00.250
It says
"yes, definitely."

21:00.250 --> 21:02.290
[ Chuckling ]
Are you serious?

21:02.290 --> 21:04.790
This is how
I picked my college.

21:04.790 --> 21:06.000
Ask a question.

21:06.000 --> 21:08.080
Uh, has Amelia lost it?

21:08.080 --> 21:09.670
Excellent.
Now pick a color.

21:09.670 --> 21:11.880
Red.
R-E-D.

21:11.880 --> 21:13.620
Now pick a number.
2.

21:16.120 --> 21:17.120
5.

21:19.170 --> 21:22.710
"100%."
See? It works.

21:22.710 --> 21:24.620
[ Both laugh ]

21:24.620 --> 21:27.500
Amelia. It's Betty.

21:27.500 --> 21:30.420
Okay.
What do we do?

21:30.420 --> 21:32.250
[ Fence rattling ]

21:32.250 --> 21:34.250
[ Grunts ]

21:34.250 --> 21:35.710
[ Whistles ]

21:35.710 --> 21:43.920
♪♪

21:43.920 --> 21:46.750
Okay. [ Clears throat ]
We're staying.

21:49.040 --> 21:52.210
Ooh. You are
some kind of genius.

21:52.210 --> 21:54.880
Well, I just
followed the recipe.

21:54.880 --> 21:56.290
So did I.
You know what?

21:56.290 --> 21:59.080
That's my problem, is I just
follow. I play it safe.

21:59.080 --> 22:00.960
Meredith: You joined
the Army during a war.

22:00.960 --> 22:02.790
You don't play it safe.

22:02.790 --> 22:05.210
No. That wasn't brave.

22:05.210 --> 22:06.880
That was Allison.

22:06.880 --> 22:08.500
Who's Allison?

22:08.500 --> 22:10.330
My favorite person on the planet
died in the second tower,

22:10.330 --> 22:12.750
which was a month after
I buried my mom

22:12.750 --> 22:15.120
and a year after
I buried my dad.

22:15.120 --> 22:18.000
She was...
She carried me.

22:19.620 --> 22:23.710
And when she died, I wished
that I had gone with her.

22:23.710 --> 22:25.540
I get that.

22:25.540 --> 22:27.920
New York was our city. I didn't
how to live there without her.

22:27.920 --> 22:31.790
So I went to Iraq, which is
where I started working

22:31.790 --> 22:35.330
with this buttoned-up,
brilliant surgeon who just --

22:35.330 --> 22:37.000
He didn't have
any doubts at all.

22:37.000 --> 22:39.460
He was such an optimist,
which I couldn't stand.

22:39.460 --> 22:41.620
He didn't try to fix me
or tell me how to grieve.

22:41.620 --> 22:43.620
He was just there,
and he was kind,

22:43.620 --> 22:45.330
and I fell in love
with him.

22:45.330 --> 22:47.750
But he had a fiancée, and
I didn't want to lose him

22:47.750 --> 22:49.710
'cause I couldn't
lose anyone else.

22:49.710 --> 22:52.290
♪♪

22:52.290 --> 22:55.000
So I played it safe.

22:55.000 --> 22:58.250
I don't hate Owen.
I...

22:58.250 --> 23:00.120
I love him.

23:01.790 --> 23:03.620
[ Bone saw buzzing ]

23:05.080 --> 23:07.000
Maggie: Isn't that
your patient?

23:09.380 --> 23:11.920
It was,
but we found a Ewing.

23:11.920 --> 23:14.120
Caught it early, so...

23:14.120 --> 23:15.670
hopefully we can get
all of it.

23:15.670 --> 23:17.500
[ Sighs ]

23:17.500 --> 23:19.040
That's amazing.

23:21.210 --> 23:24.170
Yeah. It's kind of a miracle
I was able to...

23:24.170 --> 23:26.790
find him when I did.

23:26.790 --> 23:31.120
You don't sound like somebody
who just saved a boy's life.

23:31.120 --> 23:33.210
[ Sighs ]
Yeah, it's just...

23:33.210 --> 23:35.000
Rafi's such
an active kid.

23:35.000 --> 23:37.670
He loves to swim and
climb trees and run around,

23:37.670 --> 23:39.620
and he is gonna
wake up and find out

23:39.620 --> 23:41.750
he can't ever
lift his own arm.

23:41.750 --> 23:44.380
So I'm saving his life, but
he's not gonna see it that way.

23:44.380 --> 23:48.000
He's a little kid, a little kid
who wants to play,

23:48.000 --> 23:50.380
and I'm the guy that took
that away from him.

23:50.380 --> 23:52.120
[ Sighs heavily ]

23:54.880 --> 23:56.420
My mom used to say that,

23:56.420 --> 23:59.120
"Everything's clearer
on the mountaintop."

23:59.120 --> 24:00.880
Hmm?

24:00.880 --> 24:05.250
Just, you know, when
you can get some distance,

24:05.250 --> 24:07.080
separate yourself
from your problems.

24:07.080 --> 24:08.670
They all seem
so solvable.

24:08.670 --> 24:10.920
But then you get back
into real life.

24:10.920 --> 24:14.000
Nothing is black-and-white.
Everything is just all muddy.

24:14.000 --> 24:16.500
"Everything is clearer
on the mountaintop."

24:19.120 --> 24:21.710
Guys, don't move! Don't move.
I'll be right there.

24:29.960 --> 24:31.420
Radiation? I told you
it'll fry his lung.

24:31.420 --> 24:32.750
-And the bone's already out.
-Extracorporeal radiation.

24:32.750 --> 24:34.380
The bone is already out,
so we can do

24:34.380 --> 24:36.000
the radiation
outside the body,

24:36.000 --> 24:37.500
crank up that dose
as high as we want,

24:37.500 --> 24:38.830
basically like
putting it in a microwave.

24:38.830 --> 24:40.500
It doesn't hurt him,
kills the cancer.

24:40.500 --> 24:42.170
-And all the healthy cells.
-But that won't matter.

24:42.170 --> 24:45.330
We replace the scapula,
and the framework's there
for new cells to grow back.

24:45.330 --> 24:47.960
Exactly. It gives us
a better match than any
prosthetic ever could.

24:47.960 --> 24:51.080
We re-attach the ligaments
in their natural position,
minimal loss of movement.

24:51.080 --> 24:53.290
-And no more surgeries.
-Can we do this thing?

24:53.290 --> 24:55.460
Hell yeah.
Let's move.

24:55.460 --> 24:57.540
[ Sleeping At Last's
"Taste" plays ]

24:57.540 --> 25:03.000
♪♪

25:03.000 --> 25:04.880
♪ It's bittersweet ♪

25:04.880 --> 25:06.750
♪ It's poetry ♪

25:06.750 --> 25:10.380
♪ A careful pruning
of my dead leaves ♪

25:10.380 --> 25:12.080
♪ It's holy ground ♪

25:12.080 --> 25:14.250
♪ A treasure chest ♪

25:14.250 --> 25:18.620
♪ I'm on my knees
and only scratch the surface ♪

25:18.620 --> 25:21.580
♪♪

25:21.580 --> 25:25.500
♪ We're nothing less
than a work in progress ♪

25:25.500 --> 25:29.540
♪ Sacred text on Post-it Notes ♪

25:29.540 --> 25:32.880
♪ We only speak
of a world in pieces ♪

25:32.880 --> 25:36.880
♪ Let's make a map
of what matters most ♪

25:36.880 --> 25:40.670
♪ Where every fracture
is a running river ♪

25:40.670 --> 25:43.750
♪ Leading us back
to our golden ♪

25:43.750 --> 25:50.120
♪ C-o-o-o-oasts ♪

25:50.120 --> 25:53.120
♪ Here's to showing up ♪

25:53.120 --> 25:56.620
♪ To fists unraveling ♪

25:56.620 --> 26:00.540
♪ To glass unshattering ♪

26:00.540 --> 26:04.500
♪ To breaking all the rules ♪

26:04.500 --> 26:09.040
♪ To breaking bread again ♪

26:09.040 --> 26:12.000
♪ So I propose a toast ♪

26:12.000 --> 26:15.920
♪ To fists unraveling ♪

26:15.920 --> 26:19.580
♪ To glass unshattering ♪

26:19.580 --> 26:23.500
♪ To breaking all the rules ♪

26:23.500 --> 26:26.120
♪ To breaking bread again ♪

26:26.120 --> 26:30.960
♪♪

26:30.960 --> 26:34.710
♪ We're swallowing light ♪

26:34.710 --> 26:38.380
♪ We're swallowing our pride ♪

26:38.380 --> 26:40.920
-Attachment complete.
-Good hemostasis.

26:40.920 --> 26:42.670
Jackson:
We are ready to close.

26:42.670 --> 26:44.960
[ Applause ]

26:44.960 --> 26:49.710
♪♪

26:49.710 --> 26:54.120
♪ 'Til we're fixed
from the inside ♪

26:54.120 --> 26:57.330
Unfortunately,
we've exhausted

26:57.330 --> 26:59.170
every test
that we can think of.

27:20.790 --> 27:23.080
Do -- Do you understand
what I'm saying?

27:23.080 --> 27:27.750
I understand.
But I don't accept.

27:27.750 --> 27:30.380
I don't accept your failure
to diagnose me,

27:30.380 --> 27:32.750
and I won't accept
discharge papers, either.

27:32.750 --> 27:35.290
So I'm gonna eat my sandwich,
and you're gonna go remember

27:35.290 --> 27:38.210
that you are the teacher
of Meredith Grey.

27:38.210 --> 27:39.920
Uh...

27:43.080 --> 27:46.000
Nina, w-we've
run out of tests.

27:46.000 --> 27:49.210
Then find new tests.
Invent them.

27:49.210 --> 27:50.670
Take care of me.
That is your job.

27:50.670 --> 27:52.290
[ Quietly ]
Should I page psych?

27:52.290 --> 27:53.960
[ Crying ]
I can't keep living like this.

27:53.960 --> 27:56.080
I can't keep being told
it's in my head

27:56.080 --> 27:57.920
when I know
that it's not.

27:57.920 --> 27:59.330
I can't keep
being told

27:59.330 --> 28:01.960
that I'm crazy
when I'm not crazy.

28:01.960 --> 28:04.210
If you don't help me,
I'm gonna kill myself.

28:04.210 --> 28:07.040
And then all those
doctors who said it was
in my head will be right.

28:08.580 --> 28:11.460
But they're not right.

28:11.460 --> 28:13.040
I know there's something
wrong with m--

28:13.040 --> 28:14.380
[ Groaning ]

28:14.380 --> 28:15.750
Nina?

28:15.750 --> 28:18.000
Okay. What is it?

28:18.000 --> 28:19.080
What is it?
Stomach!

28:19.080 --> 28:21.000
Here?
[ Groaning ]

28:21.000 --> 28:23.080
Alright, Dr. Webber,
uh, beds 1 and 2

28:23.080 --> 28:25.040
are ready
to be discharged,

28:25.040 --> 28:27.460
and neuro's on its way
to check the CHI in bed 6,

28:27.460 --> 28:30.580
but I did a preliminary check,
and I think he's okay.

28:30.580 --> 28:32.880
Uh...

28:32.880 --> 28:36.580
Bed 2 is Helm's patient,
and 6 is Schmitt's.

28:36.580 --> 28:38.670
[ Telephone ringing ]

28:38.670 --> 28:40.670
Yeah, well, you said show
some initiative, so...

28:40.670 --> 28:43.830
Initiative doesn't mean
doing everything yourself.

28:43.830 --> 28:45.880
Look, do you have some kind of
problem with me, Dr. Webber?

28:45.880 --> 28:48.670
Oh, far from it.
I consider you a friend.

28:48.670 --> 28:50.960
A friend? You've been on my ass
all day for nothing.

28:50.960 --> 28:52.500
I haven't made
a single mistake.

28:52.500 --> 28:54.250
I picked up
everybody else's slack.

28:54.250 --> 28:56.540
So, if there's some lesson,
please enlighten me.

28:56.540 --> 28:58.620
I don't need a friend
in the E.R., DeLuca.

28:58.620 --> 29:00.170
I need doctors
who not only

29:00.170 --> 29:02.250
can give patients
the best possible care,

29:02.250 --> 29:04.040
but teach others
to do the same.

29:04.040 --> 29:07.290
That's what separates
residents from attendings.

29:07.290 --> 29:10.540
Don't get mad at me for
thinking you've got it in ya.

29:10.540 --> 29:13.670
♪♪

29:13.670 --> 29:15.250
Ow. That hurts.

29:15.250 --> 29:18.460
Jo: I know.
Just try to relax, okay?

29:18.460 --> 29:19.830
Do you hear
something?

29:19.830 --> 29:22.420
A swooshing sound?

29:22.420 --> 29:25.120
Like her sandwich
digesting?

29:25.120 --> 29:28.250
More like
a vascular bruit.

29:28.250 --> 29:30.330
Um, here. Let's try
the ultrasound.

29:30.330 --> 29:32.120
Sure.

29:34.710 --> 29:36.670
[ Whooshing ]
[ Groans ]

29:36.670 --> 29:38.540
And to the right.

29:40.040 --> 29:41.460
I'm gonna press --

29:41.460 --> 29:43.420
-Aah! Ow.
-Sorry, sorry, sorry.

29:43.420 --> 29:45.670
Uh, take a deep
breath for me.

29:45.670 --> 29:46.670
[ Inhales deeply ]

29:46.670 --> 29:49.500
-And exhale.
-[ Exhales slowly ]

29:49.500 --> 29:51.250
[ Gasps ] There!

29:51.250 --> 29:53.960
Oh. The median
arcuate ligament.

29:53.960 --> 29:55.920
You've got MALS.
Whoa!

29:55.920 --> 29:57.670
I've only read
about this.

29:57.670 --> 30:01.960
A-A ligament is wrapped tightly
around your celiac artery.

30:01.960 --> 30:03.210
It expands
when you eat.

30:03.210 --> 30:04.710
You know,
no one's found it

30:04.710 --> 30:07.380
because you always fast
before your visits.

30:07.380 --> 30:09.710
We can go in
laparoscopically, cut it.

30:09.710 --> 30:11.670
Takes 20 minutes.

30:11.670 --> 30:14.290
♪♪

30:14.290 --> 30:15.580
I knew it was real.

30:15.580 --> 30:19.620
Oh, yeah. [ Chuckles ]
This is a real thing.

30:19.620 --> 30:22.420
-And we found it.
-Mm-hmm.

30:22.420 --> 30:24.670
And Meredith Grey
did not.

30:24.670 --> 30:26.420
♪♪

30:26.420 --> 30:28.170
I thought this
was gonna be easier.

30:28.170 --> 30:29.500
I-I don't know
how to tell him,

30:29.500 --> 30:31.000
but I don't know
how to not tell him.

30:31.000 --> 30:33.170
I feel completely
out of control.

30:33.170 --> 30:35.080
Oh, that's just the hormones.
That'll pass.

30:35.080 --> 30:37.500
Oh, it won't pass.
[ Sighs ]

30:37.500 --> 30:40.420
I mean, nothing about this
is gonna pass.

30:40.420 --> 30:42.420
Well, the "out of control"
will pass.

30:42.420 --> 30:44.620
I mean, listen,
being a mom breaks you open.

30:44.620 --> 30:45.880
It's supposed to.

30:45.880 --> 30:47.460
I mean, is --

30:47.460 --> 30:50.500
Is that what
happened to Amelia?

30:50.500 --> 30:52.420
I mean, Owen said that she
didn't want to have kids,

30:52.420 --> 30:53.580
that their marriage
was a wreck.

30:53.580 --> 30:55.210
I mean, he would call me
and say that,

30:55.210 --> 30:56.750
"She's moved out.
She's hiding from me.

30:56.750 --> 30:58.460
She doesn't want
to be married to me."

30:58.460 --> 31:00.710
And I-I didn't know
what to say to that.

31:00.710 --> 31:03.920
I know that Amelia had
a brain tumor removed, and it --

31:03.920 --> 31:05.540
but is that what suddenly

31:05.540 --> 31:07.420
made her want to have a family
and with Owen?

31:07.420 --> 31:09.290
I mean, did she change
that much?

31:09.290 --> 31:10.380
Meredith,
is she all-in?

31:10.380 --> 31:11.920
I don't know.
I'm sorry.

31:11.920 --> 31:15.790
I can't speak for Amelia,
nor do I want to try.

31:15.790 --> 31:18.330
What I do know is that you
do need to talk to him

31:18.330 --> 31:20.250
because the longer
you keep this a secret,

31:20.250 --> 31:23.120
the worse it gets
for everybody.

31:23.120 --> 31:25.290
I mean, it's not like you're
gonna lose him. It's Owen.

31:25.290 --> 31:28.250
Meredith, I know that
I'm not gonna lose him.

31:28.250 --> 31:31.000
It's -- It's Owen.

31:31.000 --> 31:34.420
He is good and honorable
and loyal and kind.

31:34.420 --> 31:37.620
And when I tell him that
I'm carrying his child,

31:37.620 --> 31:39.380
he will claim me.

31:39.380 --> 31:40.920
[ Voice breaking ] And then
for the rest of my life,

31:40.920 --> 31:43.080
I'm gonna wonder whether
he's with me out of obligation

31:43.080 --> 31:45.540
or if he really
wants to be with me.

31:45.540 --> 31:48.120
[ Door opens and closes ]

31:48.120 --> 31:50.710
Hi, babies.
How was school?

31:50.710 --> 31:52.170
-Good.
-Good.

31:52.170 --> 31:53.620
-Good?
-Mm. It smells so good in here!

31:53.620 --> 31:55.500
Yeah! Look what I have.

31:55.500 --> 31:57.830
Teddy, everything
you think you know

31:57.830 --> 31:59.790
is gonna completely change
once the baby comes.

31:59.790 --> 32:01.080
Zola:
Cookies on the table.

32:01.080 --> 32:03.290
It's not you that
you're telling him for.

32:03.290 --> 32:05.420
♪♪

32:05.420 --> 32:08.250
Hey, you want me
to take over?
I got him.

32:08.250 --> 32:09.960
You think I don't?
[ Chuckling ] No, no.

32:09.960 --> 32:11.880
The opposite, actually.
I think you're great with him.

32:11.880 --> 32:14.210
So, what's with
the staring?

32:14.210 --> 32:16.580
[ Chuckles ]
I don't know. I just...

32:16.580 --> 32:18.460
I keep kind of wondering,

32:18.460 --> 32:20.250
is this really what
broke up our marriage?

32:20.250 --> 32:22.750
Well, first of all,
brain tumor.

32:22.750 --> 32:24.290
[ Chuckles ]
I know. I know.

32:26.120 --> 32:28.290
And also...

32:28.290 --> 32:29.790
Christopher.

32:29.790 --> 32:31.460
Who?
My baby.

32:33.380 --> 32:36.290
That was his name.
Christopher.

32:36.290 --> 32:38.250
[ Inhales sharply ]

32:38.250 --> 32:40.920
I have never said that
out loud before.

32:40.920 --> 32:44.210
Not even to myself.

32:44.210 --> 32:46.460
But I loved him...

32:46.460 --> 32:49.670
for every second
of his life.

32:49.670 --> 32:51.540
I loved him so much.

32:53.000 --> 32:56.120
After he died,
the pain was unbearable.

32:56.120 --> 32:58.830
And I think
I became afraid

32:58.830 --> 33:01.710
that loving
another baby

33:01.710 --> 33:05.290
would somehow lessen
Christopher's memory.

33:05.290 --> 33:08.170
But I'm okay.

33:08.170 --> 33:09.880
I couldn't
say his name before,

33:09.880 --> 33:12.920
and now I feel like for
the first time in my life,

33:12.920 --> 33:15.040
I can talk about him,
and I-I don't feel like

33:15.040 --> 33:18.000
it's gonna break me,
you know?

33:18.000 --> 33:21.170
And I can look at
Leo and Betty and --

33:21.170 --> 33:23.620
and know that...

33:23.620 --> 33:26.040
they can't erase him.

33:26.040 --> 33:27.750
Nothing can.

33:29.250 --> 33:31.460
And that's
a good thing.

33:31.460 --> 33:35.000
♪♪

33:41.960 --> 33:42.830
[ Indistinct conversations ]

33:42.830 --> 33:44.790
Oh. You found us.

33:44.790 --> 33:47.330
Were you guys seriously
out here all day?

33:47.330 --> 33:48.750
[ Door closes ]

33:48.750 --> 33:50.040
How was your day?

33:50.040 --> 33:52.120
Fine.

33:52.120 --> 33:53.790
That's all
we're gonna get?

33:53.790 --> 33:55.210
Fine,
and I didn't do drugs.

33:55.210 --> 33:56.420
That'll do.

33:56.420 --> 34:00.250
♪♪

34:00.250 --> 34:03.750
Does Owen
wear dad jeans?

34:03.750 --> 34:05.960
[ Chuckles ]

34:05.960 --> 34:07.830
Okay.
To your car seat.

34:07.830 --> 34:09.040
"Yes, definitely."

34:13.250 --> 34:15.330
Alright, I'm gonna
go talk to Rafi's dad.

34:15.330 --> 34:17.080
You earned it.

34:17.080 --> 34:18.540
Hey, could you hold up
a sec, Chief?

34:18.540 --> 34:19.790
Why?

34:19.790 --> 34:22.000
Uh, because ever since
you found out

34:22.000 --> 34:23.580
that Jo and I
are friends,

34:23.580 --> 34:26.380
you've looked like
you want to kill me.

34:28.250 --> 34:30.380
Uh, so I just wanted
to clear the air.

34:30.380 --> 34:32.210
There was nothing between us.
She's like my sister.

34:32.210 --> 34:34.420
Did you know Paul?

34:34.420 --> 34:36.210
Because a good brother
would have protected her.

34:36.210 --> 34:38.120
You're twice that guy's size.
You could have leveled him.

34:38.120 --> 34:39.420
I met him.
I didn't like him.

34:39.420 --> 34:41.290
I told her so.
She didn't listen to me.

34:41.290 --> 34:42.790
I mean, Jo was not
the best listener

34:42.790 --> 34:44.500
of other people's ideas
back then.

34:44.500 --> 34:45.920
Yeah. She still isn't.

34:45.920 --> 34:47.580
Well, I didn't like him,
and he didn't like me.

34:47.580 --> 34:50.040
Jo said he was jealous
of our friendship,

34:50.040 --> 34:51.460
and she started
to back away.

34:51.460 --> 34:53.540
I-I thought
I was being respectful.

34:53.540 --> 34:56.170
I had no idea he was...

34:56.170 --> 34:58.000
I didn't like the guy,
but I swear to God,

34:58.000 --> 35:01.540
if I had known, yeah...
I would've leveled him.

35:01.540 --> 35:06.000
♪♪

35:06.000 --> 35:08.000
[ Door opens ]

35:08.000 --> 35:09.750
[ Monitor beeping ]

35:09.750 --> 35:11.170
Hey.

35:15.080 --> 35:16.880
Well...
[Clears throat]

35:16.880 --> 35:18.540
I'm still mad
at Jackson.

35:18.540 --> 35:20.540
[ Chuckles ]
Kind of.

35:20.540 --> 35:23.670
But I think, uh,
mostly I'm mad at me.

35:23.670 --> 35:25.620
'Cause you're right.
I have big questions.

35:25.620 --> 35:27.250
And I haven't
been asking them

35:27.250 --> 35:28.830
because I've been wrapped up
in everyone else's,

35:28.830 --> 35:30.580
which needs to stop.

35:30.580 --> 35:32.210
So, thank you.

35:32.210 --> 35:35.170
So happy for you, Maggie.
[ Chuckles ]

35:35.170 --> 35:37.040
I don't suppose
you also came in here

35:37.040 --> 35:39.420
to tell me
you found a donor?

35:39.420 --> 35:41.080
Not yet.

35:41.080 --> 35:42.750
But I haven't
given up hope yet.

35:42.750 --> 35:44.710
And neither should you.
Deal?

35:44.710 --> 35:47.170
Deal.

35:47.170 --> 35:56.380
♪♪

35:56.380 --> 35:58.880
[ Sniffles ]

35:58.880 --> 36:02.080
[ "The Thrill is Gone"
plays on guitar ]

36:02.080 --> 36:04.330
[ Indistinct conversations ]

36:04.330 --> 36:10.580
♪♪

36:10.580 --> 36:15.000
Richard:
♪ The thrill is gone ♪

36:15.000 --> 36:18.670
♪ The thrill is gone away ♪

36:18.670 --> 36:20.920
♪ Mm-hmm ♪

36:20.920 --> 36:23.580
♪ The thrill is gone, baby ♪

36:23.580 --> 36:25.120
♪ Mm ♪

36:25.120 --> 36:28.000
♪ The thrill is gone away ♪

36:28.000 --> 36:30.040
♪ Mm, mm ♪

36:30.040 --> 36:34.000
♪ You know you done me wrong ♪

36:34.000 --> 36:37.830
♪ And you'll be sorry someday ♪

36:37.830 --> 36:39.750
♪ The thrill is gone ♪

36:39.750 --> 36:41.460
[ Door bells jingle ]

36:41.460 --> 36:43.620
♪♪

36:43.620 --> 36:46.460
♪ It's gone away from me ♪

36:46.460 --> 36:48.620
♪♪

36:48.620 --> 36:50.620
♪ The thrill is gone ♪

36:50.620 --> 36:52.960
Hey. Schmitt,
you made it.

36:52.960 --> 36:56.420
♪ It's gone away from me ♪

36:56.420 --> 36:58.580
♪ Mmm-mm ♪

36:58.580 --> 37:03.210
♪ The thrill is gone, baby ♪

37:03.210 --> 37:05.500
♪ The thrill
is gone away from me ♪

37:05.500 --> 37:07.920
I may have misread
the situation.

37:07.920 --> 37:09.250
♪ Although
I'll still live on ♪

37:09.250 --> 37:12.250
Sorry.

37:12.250 --> 37:16.120
♪ But so lonely I'll be,
uh-huh ♪

37:20.250 --> 37:21.960
Hey. I scheduled
Nina's laparoscopy

37:21.960 --> 37:23.750
for first thing
tomorrow.

37:23.750 --> 37:25.830
[ Flatly ] Great.

37:28.790 --> 37:32.080
I-I know that we have
a lot of approaches,

37:32.080 --> 37:34.460
but that's good, right?

37:34.460 --> 37:36.080
The -- The right one's
in there somewhere.

37:36.080 --> 37:37.960
I'm not worried
about that.

37:40.710 --> 37:42.080
What is it?

37:42.080 --> 37:44.710
Okay. Process
of elimination.

37:44.710 --> 37:49.710
I have systematically removed
stressors from my life --

37:49.710 --> 37:52.880
less coffee, more exercise,
better food.

37:52.880 --> 37:54.540
I'm still stressed.

37:54.540 --> 37:58.250
I've taken on fewer patients.
Still stressed.

37:58.250 --> 38:01.210
So I took
the extreme measure

38:01.210 --> 38:03.920
of stepping back
from the job

38:03.920 --> 38:08.580
I have spent my entire career
working for.

38:08.580 --> 38:11.750
And even though your husband
now has all that stress,

38:11.750 --> 38:13.170
I'm still stressed.

38:13.170 --> 38:19.080
So if I'm rational,
if I'm scientific,

38:19.080 --> 38:21.380
I must look elsewhere for
the source of that stress.

38:21.380 --> 38:22.960
What else is there?

38:25.790 --> 38:27.580
[ Chuckles ]

38:27.580 --> 38:29.790
My husband...

38:29.790 --> 38:31.500
is a firefighter.

38:31.500 --> 38:34.000
I haven't heard
from him today.

38:34.000 --> 38:38.080
And when I don't hear from him,
I don't breathe.

38:38.080 --> 38:40.960
Okay.
Ben Warren adores you.

38:43.500 --> 38:46.210
I know his job
is scary, but...

38:46.210 --> 38:48.040
you two are good.

38:48.040 --> 38:50.040
You two are the goal.

38:52.380 --> 38:56.710
Good work today.
I'll see you in the morning.

38:56.710 --> 39:00.500
Surgeons are trained
to provide care for others.

39:00.500 --> 39:04.880
♪♪

39:04.880 --> 39:08.790
[ Exhales shakily ]
He's okay?

39:08.790 --> 39:11.830
He's gonna experience
a little pain for a while

39:11.830 --> 39:13.670
and have to do
physical therapy,

39:13.670 --> 39:15.670
but, yeah,
everything looks good.

39:15.670 --> 39:17.830
He did great
in there.

39:17.830 --> 39:19.170
[ Exhales deeply ]

39:19.170 --> 39:21.670
♪ That there is an ending ♪

39:21.670 --> 39:22.750
-Thank you.
-Yeah.

39:22.750 --> 39:24.580
Thank you so much.

39:24.580 --> 39:25.960
♪ I know the light
will always find us ♪

39:25.960 --> 39:30.330
♪ But the shadows
just remind us ♪

39:30.330 --> 39:32.120
Some biologists
believe it's human nature,

39:32.120 --> 39:35.120
the desire to help.

39:35.120 --> 39:41.040
♪ Take it all away, we'll stay ♪

39:41.040 --> 39:42.620
Can I kiss you,
please?

39:42.620 --> 39:44.330
[ Chuckles ]

39:44.330 --> 39:46.000
We did it.

39:46.000 --> 39:48.540
We saved his life...
and his quality of life.

39:48.540 --> 39:50.500
--Congratulations.
No, no. "We," okay?

39:50.500 --> 39:52.500
Both of us.
You -- it was your idea.

39:52.500 --> 39:54.250
You know,
we did this together.

39:54.250 --> 39:56.960
Are you leaving
again tomorrow?

39:56.960 --> 39:59.170
No. No.
I'm done being gone.

39:59.170 --> 40:01.330
This is where
I feel most connected

40:01.330 --> 40:03.250
to something
larger than me --

40:03.250 --> 40:05.710
in the O.R., doing something
that I'm great at.

40:05.710 --> 40:07.250
I had an
amazing day today,

40:07.250 --> 40:09.170
best day I've had
in a very long time,

40:09.170 --> 40:10.750
and you are
a huge part of that.

40:10.750 --> 40:13.710
♪ 'Cause we're bound together ♪

40:13.710 --> 40:18.040
I apologize for the way
that I left, truly, okay?

40:18.040 --> 40:20.460
That will not
happen again.

40:20.460 --> 40:22.000
♪ We'll find our way home ♪

40:22.000 --> 40:23.580
I can't have dinner
with you tonight.

40:23.580 --> 40:25.080
-[ Groans ]
-[ Chuckles ]

40:25.080 --> 40:29.210
I need to work on
my rechargeable hearts.

40:29.210 --> 40:32.040
Jackson, this is --
this is my mountaintop.

40:32.040 --> 40:33.920
They may not be able
to help Cece,

40:33.920 --> 40:35.790
but they're gonna help
a lot of other people.

40:35.790 --> 40:38.080
[ Inhales sharply ]

40:38.080 --> 40:40.750
But, yes.
Please do kiss me.

40:40.750 --> 40:43.670
♪ That won't seem to let go ♪

40:43.670 --> 40:45.580
♪ Every day falls behind us ♪

40:45.580 --> 40:47.290
Scientists believe
we're biologically

40:47.290 --> 40:50.210
programmed to empathize.

40:50.210 --> 40:51.580
I think it's one of the reasons

40:51.580 --> 40:53.830
our species
has lasted this long.

40:53.830 --> 40:55.710
You're coming home.

40:55.710 --> 40:57.920
I was in an O.R. all day.
I'm behind.

40:57.920 --> 40:59.960
So, be behind.
We're newlyweds.

40:59.960 --> 41:01.670
We should be doing
newlywed things.

41:01.670 --> 41:03.290
Mm. Like what?

41:03.290 --> 41:05.750
Um, if you can't think
of anything,

41:05.750 --> 41:07.210
then I want
an annulment.

41:07.210 --> 41:09.960
[ Chuckling ] Okay.
Okay. I'm coming.

41:09.960 --> 41:11.830
♪ Try, try to shake us ♪

41:11.830 --> 41:13.960
I heard you worked
with Link today.

41:13.960 --> 41:17.040
Yep. Seems like
a pretty good guy.

41:17.040 --> 41:19.250
[ Keys clacking ]

41:19.250 --> 41:21.000
♪ 'Cause we're bound together ♪

41:21.000 --> 41:23.000
What are you doing?

41:23.000 --> 41:25.710
♪ High, higher we'll go ♪

41:25.710 --> 41:27.420
♪ Fight fire with hope ♪

41:27.420 --> 41:31.500
We have an innate instinct
to support each other.

41:31.500 --> 41:34.040
You can only take care
of yourself for so long.

41:34.040 --> 41:35.750
-Thank you.
-I should be thanking you.

41:35.750 --> 41:37.540
You made them.
No, I meant for today.

41:37.540 --> 41:39.380
It was nice to talk to someone
other than room service.

41:39.380 --> 41:40.710
Well, I'm always here.

41:40.710 --> 41:43.040
but I'm not the one
you should be talking to.

41:43.040 --> 41:44.790
♪ We'll find our way home ♪

41:44.790 --> 41:48.250
♪ 'Cause we're bound together,
we're bound together ♪

41:48.250 --> 41:50.380
Amelia: Hello? Mer?
Ooh, cookies!

41:50.380 --> 41:52.380
♪ We'll find our way home ♪

41:52.380 --> 41:54.330
These are amazing.
What are you doing here?

41:54.330 --> 41:56.120
I was just picking up
some things.

41:56.120 --> 41:59.330
I think I'm gonna be at Owen's
a little longer than I planned.

41:59.330 --> 42:01.120
Because let's face it --

42:01.120 --> 42:04.040
some problems are way too big
to carry on our own.

42:17.330 --> 42:25.420
♪♪

42:25.420 --> 42:33.710
♪♪

42:33.710 --> 42:42.000
♪♪
